      "name": "Recursive CTE",
      "sql": "WITH RECURSIVE org(id, name, level) AS (\n  SELECT id, name, 1 FROM employees WHERE manager_id IS NULL\n  UNION ALL\n  SELECT e.id, e.name, o.level + 1\n  FROM employees e\n  JOIN org o ON e.manager_id = o.id\n)\nSELECT name, level FROM org ORDER BY level, name;",
      "explanation": "### Goal\nLabel each employee with their depth in the org chart: CEO is level `1`, direct reports level `2`, and so on.\n\n### Walking the query\n\n**1. `WITH RECURSIVE org(id, name, level) AS (...)`** — a recursive CTE that carries three columns forward: the employee `id` (needed to join children to parents), the `name` (what we report), and a running `level` counter.\n\n**2. The anchor — `SELECT id, name, 1 FROM employees WHERE manager_id IS NULL`** — the CEO is the only employee whose `manager_id` is `NULL`, so this seeds the recursion with exactly one row (Alice) at `level = 1`. Note the test must be `IS NULL`, not `= NULL` — in SQL, `= NULL` is never true.\n\n**3. `UNION ALL`** — appends each newly-discovered level to the result.\n\n**4. The recursive member** —\n```\nSELECT e.id, e.name, o.level + 1\nFROM employees e\nJOIN org o ON e.manager_id = o.id\n```\nThis is the heart of the walk. On each iteration it joins the *base* `employees` table to the rows produced so far (`org`). The join condition `e.manager_id = o.id` reads as: *find every employee `e` whose manager is one of the people we already placed*. Those children inherit `o.level + 1` — one deeper than their manager.\n\n- Iteration 1 starts from Alice (level 1) → finds Bob, Carol (level 2).\n- Iteration 2 starts from Bob, Carol → finds Dan, Eve, Grace (level 3).\n- Iteration 3 starts from those → finds Frank (level 4).\n- Iteration 4 finds no children → recursion stops naturally.\n\n**Termination** here is implicit: the tree is finite, so eventually the recursive member produces no new rows. No explicit `WHERE` brake is needed.\n\n**5. `SELECT name, level FROM org ORDER BY level, name`** — outputs the two requested columns, ordered by level then name (alphabetical within a level), matching the required output ordering."
