      "sql": "WITH RECURSIVE chain(id, name, path) AS (\n  SELECT id, name, name FROM employees WHERE manager_id IS NULL\n  UNION ALL\n  SELECT e.id, e.name, c.path || ' > ' || e.name\n  FROM employees e\n  JOIN chain c ON e.manager_id = c.id\n)\nSELECT name, path FROM chain ORDER BY path;",
      "explanation": "### Goal\nFor each employee, build a breadcrumb `path` of names from the CEO down to them, joined with ` > ` (e.g. `Alice > Bob > Dan > Frank`).\n\n### Walking the query\n\n**1. `WITH RECURSIVE chain(id, name, path) AS (...)`** — carries the employee `id` (for joining), the `name`, and an accumulating `path` string.\n\n**2. The anchor — `SELECT id, name, name FROM employees WHERE manager_id IS NULL`** — seeds with the CEO. Crucially, the `path` is initialized to just the CEO's own name (`name` is selected a second time *as* the path). So Alice's starting path is simply `'Alice'`.\n\n**3. The recursive member** —\n```\nSELECT e.id, e.name, c.path || ' > ' || e.name\nFROM employees e\nJOIN chain c ON e.manager_id = c.id\n```\nThe same parent→child join as the level problem, but instead of incrementing a number we **accumulate a string**. `||` is SQLite's string-concatenation operator. For each child `e`, we take the parent's already-built path `c.path`, append `' > '`, then append the child's own name. Because the parent's path already contains the whole chain above it, this extends the breadcrumb one link at a time.\n\n- Alice → `'Alice'`\n- Bob (child of Alice) → `'Alice' || ' > ' || 'Bob'` = `'Alice > Bob'`\n- Dan (child of Bob) → `'Alice > Bob > Dan'`\n- Frank (child of Dan) → `'Alice > Bob > Dan > Frank'`\n\nThe finite tree guarantees termination — no explicit stop condition required.\n\n**4. `SELECT name, path FROM chain ORDER BY path`** — returns the name and its full path, ordered lexicographically by the path string (so all of Alice's subtree sorts together).\n\n### Gotcha\nThe order of the two `name` references in the anchor matters: the *first* feeds the `name` column, the *second* seeds `path`. Forgetting to initialize `path` with the CEO's name would leave the breadcrumb missing its root."
