      "sql": "WITH global AS (\n  SELECT AVG(amount) AS g FROM orders\n),\nper_cust AS (\n  SELECT customer, AVG(amount) AS cust_avg FROM orders GROUP BY customer\n)\nSELECT customer, ROUND(cust_avg, 2) AS cust_avg\nFROM per_cust, global\nWHERE cust_avg > g\nORDER BY cust_avg DESC;",
      "explanation": "### Goal\nFind customers whose **per-customer average order** exceeds the **global average order** across all orders.\n\n### Why two CTEs\nWe need two different aggregates at two different grains: one number for the whole table, and one number per customer. Naming them as CTEs keeps the final query readable.\n\n### Walking the query\n\n**1. `global AS (SELECT AVG(amount) AS g FROM orders)`** — collapses the entire `orders` table to a single row, `g` = the global average order amount. Across all 7 orders the mean is `(120+80+300+260+40+60+500)/7 = 1360/7 ≈ 194.29`.\n\n**2. `per_cust AS (SELECT customer, AVG(amount) AS cust_avg FROM orders GROUP BY customer)`** — one row per customer with their personal average:\n- Ava → 100, Ben → 280, Cyd → 50, Dan → 500.\n\n**3. The join — `FROM per_cust, global`** — the comma is an implicit **cross join**. Since `global` has exactly one row, cross-joining simply staples the single value `g` onto every `per_cust` row, making `g` available for comparison. (A one-row cross join is the idiomatic way to bring a scalar aggregate alongside grouped rows.)\n\n**4. `WHERE cust_avg > g`** — keep only customers above the global mean. Ben (280) and Dan (500) pass; Ava (100) and Cyd (50) are below ≈194.29 and are dropped.\n\n**5. `SELECT customer, ROUND(cust_avg, 2) … ORDER BY cust_avg DESC`** — report the customer and their average rounded to 2 decimals, highest first → Dan (500.00), then Ben (280.00).\n\n### Result\n```\nDan | 500.0\nBen | 280.0\n```"
