      "explanation": "### Goal\nAmong **in-stock** products (`stock > 0`), return those priced above the average price **of the in-stock items only**.\n\n### The subtle part: define the population once\nThe trap is computing the average over *all* products instead of just the in-stock ones. Out-of-stock items (Mouse at 25, Lamp at 30) must not enter the average. The CTE makes the filtered population a named set we can reuse, so the filter is written once and can't drift between the row list and the average.\n\n### Walking the query\n\n**1. `WITH in_stock AS (SELECT * FROM products WHERE stock > 0)`** — defines the population: Keyboard (45), Monitor (220), Desk (180), Chair (140), Cable (8). Mouse and Lamp are excluded because their stock is 0.\n\n**2. `(SELECT AVG(price) FROM in_stock)`** — the average is taken **over the CTE**, i.e. only the in-stock items: `(45 + 220 + 180 + 140 + 8) / 5 = 593 / 5 = 118.6`. This is the whole reason for the CTE: both the row source and the average reference the *same* filtered set.\n\n**3. `WHERE price > 118.6`** — keep in-stock items priced above 118.6: Monitor (220), Desk (180), Chair (140). Keyboard (45) and Cable (8) fall below.\n\n**4. `ORDER BY price DESC`** — most expensive first.\n\n### Result\n```\nMonitor | 220.0\nDesk    | 180.0\nChair   | 140.0\n```"
