      "explanation": "### Same result with a window average\nHere a single subquery both filters to in-stock rows and attaches the in-stock average to every row via `AVG(price) OVER ()`.\n\n### Walking the query\n\n**1. Inner query: `... FROM products WHERE stock > 0`** — first restrict to the five in-stock products. The `WHERE` runs *before* the window function, so the window only ever sees in-stock rows.\n\n**2. `AVG(price) OVER ()`** — an empty `OVER ()` means *the whole result set* (all in-stock rows) is the window. It computes the average price (118.6) and writes it onto **every** row, without collapsing the rows the way `GROUP BY` would. This is the key difference from a plain aggregate: we keep all rows *and* get the group average beside each.\n\n**3. Outer `WHERE price > avg_price`** — filters using the per-row average column. We need the outer query because the window column `avg_price` isn't visible to the inner `WHERE`.\n\n**4. `ORDER BY price DESC`** — same final ordering.\n\n### Why it matches\nBecause the in-stock filter is applied before the window, `AVG(price) OVER ()` equals exactly the `(SELECT AVG(price) FROM in_stock)` of the first approach (118.6). The same three products clear the bar in the same order: Monitor, Desk, Chair."
